                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311201-197-off1050 t18311201-197-crimeloc1053"></join>. On the evening of the 31st of October, I saw a piece of merino moving from our shop, near the door; I called to Mr. Humphreys<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183112010094"></xptr>and told him - he ran to the door, and I followed him; the prisoner was brought back by the officer, with the merino in his possession.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-197-person1573">
                  HERBERT 
                  KING
               <interp inst="t18311201-197-person1573" type="surname" value="KING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-197-person1573" type="given" value="HERBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-197-person1573" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-officer. I saw the prisoner fifteen or eighteen yards from the prosecutor's shop; he tapped me on the shoulder, and said, "Take notice of me;" I looked at him, not knowing what to make of him - he walked on to the prosecutor's shop, and took this piece from a parcel near the door.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I was in distress, and thought if I was sent out of the country I should get employ, and told the officer to watch me.</p>
